import BlogPost from "~/layouts/BlogPost.astro";

const content = {
	title: "A Better Webcam Setup",
	description:
		"How to get a clean, professional video feed for calls using a real camera, a capture card, and a dedicated USB hub.",
	pubDate: "Jun 16 2026",
	slug: "good-webcam-setup",
};
---

<BlogPost content={content}>
	<p>
		It's 2026. Being on video is unavoidable. Even if you prefer being in office
		and meeting IRL, video call platforms are part of most meeting. So are
		bad picture quality, flat lighting, and absurd framing.
	</p>
	
	<p>
		One of the best upgrades I ever made to my home office was upgrading from the built-in Apple Display webcam to a proper prosumer camera rig. 
	</p>

	<p>
		The key take-away: use a real camera, get a clean signal off of it with a capture card, and feed
		that signal through a <em>dedicated</em> USB hub. Each piece matters, and the order you chain them
		together matters too.
	</p>

	<h2>1. The camera</h2>

	<ul>
		<li>
			<a href="https://www.amazon.com/Canon-EOS-Rebel-SL3-18-55mm/dp/B07PJW1GBZ"
				>Canon Rebel SL3</a
			>, with the 18-55mm f4-5.6 kit lens.
			<ul>
				<li>
					There are many digital cameras, but this one is mine. I originally chose it because of its
					on-board USB output, which means you can skip the capture card entirely and get a clean
					feed directly from the camera over USB.
				</li>
				<li>
					The only catch is that the USB feed is limited to 576p30, which you don't notice until you
					take a still photo and view it at 2k or 4k. This is a digital camera with a big sensor that
					captures enormously large raw photos, so why the low-res video feed? Turns out the on-board
					USB output is USB 2.0(!) and therefore limited on how much data it can transfer.
				</li>
				<li>
					With the limitations of the on-board USB established, the move is to ignore it and pull a
					clean signal off the mini HDMI port instead. That's where the capture card comes in.
				</li>
			</ul>
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>2. The capture card</h2>

	<ul>
		<li>
			<a href="https://www.elgato.com/us/en/p/game-capture-4k-x">Elgato 4K Capture card</a>
			<ul>
				<li>
					This is plugged into the mini HDMI port on the camera and into a USB 3.0 hub, and from
					there onto the computer. Elgato makes great stuff. This is the second capture device I've
					used of theirs and they've both worked flawlessly in both Windows and Mac. I'm sure Linux
					is its own special hell with these things, but you get what you're paying for.
				</li>
				<li>
					You'll also need a <a
						href="https://www.amazon.com/AmazonBasics-High-Speed-Mini-HDMI-Cable/dp/B014I8U33A"
						>mini HDMI to HDMI cable</a
					> to get the signal from the camera to the card.
				</li>
			</ul>
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>3. The USB hub (this is the important one)</h2>

	<ul>
		<li>
			A <em>dedicated</em>
			<a href="https://www.amazon.com/Anker-Aluminum-Ethernet-MacBook-ChromeBook/dp/B00YULTJ24"
				>USB 3.0 hub</a
			> — this is really important. The capture card transfers a lot of data and is picky about what
			it can be chained through.
			<ul>
				<li>
					In a previous iteration of my setup I had a monitor with an integrated USB 3.0 hub, which
					I learned didn't have enough bandwidth for 1080p60. So I shopped around until I found a hub
					that had enough bandwidth and an ethernet port.
				</li>
				<li>
					This hub goes directly to my MacBook Pro for exactly two things: camera signal and
					ethernet. Because I only need 1080p60, the addition of gigabit ethernet doesn't cut into
					the bandwidth needed to do video.
				</li>
				<li>
					And wired ethernet makes for more consistent call quality! An absolute must-have if you
					take lots of calls and want good video <em>and</em> audio.
				</li>
				<li>
					Bonus: a hub with its own power adapter can power the camera rig through a <a
						href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07BNP6PVK">dummy battery / AC adapter</a
					>, so you never have to think about charging it.
				</li>
			</ul>
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>4. Mounting and placement</h2>

	<p>
		How the camera is positioned matters as much as the camera itself. Get it stable, get it at the
		right distance, and get it at eye level.
	</p>

	<ul>
		<li>
			<a href="https://joby.com/global/ballhead-5k-jb01514-bww/">Joby BallHead</a> — a small,
			solid ball head lets you dial in the exact angle and then forget about it. Pair it with
			whatever mount makes sense for your desk: a
			<a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07K7QHZ8F">desk clamp arm</a> keeps the camera off the
			desktop and out of the way, and the ball head handles the fine adjustments.
		</li>
		<li>
			Position the camera 2-3 feet from your face and at roughly eye level. Closer than that and the
			lens distorts your features; much farther and you lose the sense of presence that makes a real
			camera worth the trouble. Eye level is the key part — a camera looking up your nose or down at
			the top of your head reads as unflattering and slightly off, no matter how good the glass is.
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>5. Lighting</h2>

	<p>
		A real camera in a poorly lit room still looks bad. One good key light fixes most of it.
	</p>

	<ul>
		<li>
			<a href="https://www.elgato.com/us/en/p/key-light">Elgato Key Light</a> — bright, dimmable, and
			adjustable in color temperature, all controllable from software. Set it up off to one side and
			slightly above eye line and you're done.
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Putting it together</h2>

	<ol>
		<li>Camera → mini HDMI out → capture card.</li>
		<li>Capture card → dedicated USB 3.0 hub.</li>
		<li>USB 3.0 hub → computer (carrying camera signal and ethernet).</li>
		<li>Camera on a ball head, 2-3 feet away at eye level, with a key light off to one side.</li>
	</ol>

	<p>
		That's the whole thing. It's more involved than a clip-on webcam, but the payoff is a feed that
		looks like you put thought into it.
	</p>
</BlogPost>
